CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved  - JFC response to email:  Dear Mr. Dobson:  Thank you for your email to Metrolist (quoted below).  MetroList is a free service to the current or former residents of Boston.  MetroList is a walk-in program at Boston City Hall  room 966. In-person hours are 9AM-4PM  Monday to Friday (except for holidays).   We understand your frustration regarding your housing search.  Even though Boston's housing stock is more than 20% restricted affordable units  it is still not enough to meet the demand. The same is true for Housing Choice Vouchers and Massachusetts Rental Voucher Program.  More than 50% of your income towards rent is considered rent-burdened  and that makes your situation all the more difficult; some properties in Boston and surrounding communities (typically those older developments with federal housing assistance funds) have preferences for families who are rent-burdened.   Having enough housing to meet the demand is one of the concerns that the City is trying to address in its Housing a Changing City: Boston 2030 Plan (found here:  http://www.cityofboston.gov/dnd/boston2030.asp)   You can also participate in community meetings on the City's Action Plan (see the Action Plan in this list of event:  http://www.trumba.com/events-calendar/ma/boston/boston/city-calendar-department-of-neighborhood-development)   We first suggest that you contact Boston Housing Authority to inquire about your aplpiaciton status; you can also apply for other programs.   From the Boston Housing Authority website:  http://www.bostonhousing.org/en/For-Applicants/How-Do-I-Apply-for-BHA-Housing.aspx Checking the Status of Your Application The waiting time to begin the screening or final eligibility process varies from 10 weeks to over five years from your date of application  depending on the number of bedrooms and type of unit your household requires  your priority and preference points  and the number of units at the communities you have selected. A communitys waiting list may range from 1 200 to 13 000 applicants.  It is impossible to identify what number families rank on the waiting lists as this number may vary daily. Therefore  BHA may only provide a rough estimate of when a family might be selected for the final eligibility screening process.  Applicants may check their application status by calling the Status Information Line at (617) 988-3400  or visiting the Housing Service Center (56 Chauncy Street  Boston  MA 02111) Monday through Wednesday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.     To assist you with your housing search  MetroList  also known as the Metropolitan Housing Opportunity Clearing Center  is a one-stop rental housing information center. MetroList provides information on apartment listings  open waitlists  market-rate listings  homeownership opportunities  and local services  as well as guidance to low-income tenants as how to apply for subsidized apartments.   For listings to be sent by first-class mail or e-mail  constituents must first complete the Metrolist intake form  which can be found here:  http://www.cityofboston.gov/fairhousing/fairhousing/metrolist.asp  This form assists us in providing the listings in your communities of choice.  If you use the e-service form  please allow at least 3-5 days for your request to be sent to you by mail/email.   If you are not a Boston resident  or if you are seeking additional resources and housing opportunities  please review the information and websites below.   CHAPA has produced a booklet with information about searching for rental housing in Massachusetts for people who have one or more disabilities. Most of the information is also helpful to people who are low-income.  To download a copy  visit:  http://www.chapa.org/sites/default/files/HousingSearchGuide_2014_1.pdf   The Boston Redevelopment Authority (BRA) sponsors the development of affordable housing in the City of Boston under the Inclusionary Development Program.  First  start here: http://www.bostonredevelopmen...
